at least in the hierarchy that I sort of in a fake way made here.

00:04:59.519 --> 00:05:02.000
So, you'll notice this looks really similar.

00:05:02.000 --> 00:05:08.160
The sort of first next step is that instead of a CSV file that's on your laptop, you can

00:05:08.160 --> 00:05:11.279
deal with a Parquet file that is on your laptop.

00:05:11.279 --> 00:05:15.920
So, a Parquet file is a, it's a binary file format.

00:05:15.920 --> 00:05:21.279
So, in that sense, you can't like open it in a text editor and like see the rows, but

00:05:21.279 --> 00:05:26.959
it is a file format that is used to store rectangular data along with metadata like

00:05:26.959 --> 00:05:30.559
the column name and metadata about what the type is.

00:05:30.559 --> 00:05:35.440
So, it's specially made to deal with rectangular data.

00:05:35.440 --> 00:05:41.359
And the thing that is great about Parquet files is that we have ways to run queries

00:05:41.359 --> 00:05:42.799
on the file.

00:05:42.799 --> 00:05:48.720
So, the code that you write, you'll notice looks really similar to the code that I wrote

00:05:48.720 --> 00:05:49.200
before.

00:05:49.200 --> 00:05:55.359
Instead of doing a read CSV, I'm using a different function from, in this case, DuckPlier.

00:05:55.359 --> 00:05:59.119
And so, I'm going to say read Parquet DuckDB.

00:05:59.119 --> 00:06:00.160
Here's the thing.

00:06:00.160 --> 00:06:05.519
When I run that file, when I run that line there, it actually is not reading the whole

00:06:05.519 --> 00:06:06.720
file into memory.

00:06:06.720 --> 00:06:12.239
It is looking at the file and understanding what's in it, but the whole file is not being

00:06:12.239 --> 00:06:13.679
brought into memory.

00:06:13.679 --> 00:06:19.440
I can write code against this object that kind of acts like a data frame, but actually

00:06:19.440 --> 00:06:24.720
is not a fully in-memory data frame in R. So, I can do something like a, like a, like

00:06:24.720 --> 00:06:27.679
a group by summarize, including an arrange here.

00:06:27.679 --> 00:06:30.160
And I get out results like this.

00:06:30.160 --> 00:06:34.079
I want to highlight for you that it doesn't say it's a table.

00:06:34.079 --> 00:06:38.720
And if you were using non-tidy verse, it wouldn't say it's a data frame in this case, because

00:06:38.720 --> 00:06:46.160
it actually has not been brought over the wire, if you will, into R at all yet.

00:06:46.160 --> 00:06:49.200
There is no data frame in R at this case.

00:06:49.200 --> 00:06:53.839
If I decided I wanted to bring it into R, I would do something like this.

00:06:54.000 --> 00:07:01.600
Explicitly say, okay, I need to collect it from this sort of hazy, it's not really materialized

00:07:01.600 --> 00:07:03.839
yet, into an actual R object.

00:07:03.839 --> 00:07:06.720
So, now it is a regular R object.

00:07:06.720 --> 00:07:13.600
So, this solves problems both about memory and performance, because you don't have to

00:07:13.600 --> 00:07:15.839
bring the whole thing into memory.

00:07:15.839 --> 00:07:19.519
You can just bring a summarized result into memory.

00:07:19.519 --> 00:07:25.040
Instead of bringing every single row over into R, you can just bring the summarized

00:07:26.160 --> 00:07:30.720
data that you need into R, that you might need to make a visualization or to train a

00:07:30.720 --> 00:07:31.519
model.

00:07:31.519 --> 00:07:37.920
When you're working, so this is this sort of, sort of initial kind of architecture.

00:07:37.920 --> 00:07:44.320
Just you switch out a CSV for a parquet file, and this helps you with performance, because

00:07:44.320 --> 00:07:51.200
it turns out DuckDB is a really efficient and fast query engine.

00:07:51.200 --> 00:08:00.559
It can run queries faster than even some of the, like, powered by C, say, dplyr operations

00:08:00.559 --> 00:08:01.760
or data table.

00:08:01.760 --> 00:08:10.799
Like, DuckDB as an engine for queries is faster than anything we can do from R in many situations.

00:08:10.799 --> 00:08:15.920
So, it both solves the memory performance and the performance, the memory problems and

00:08:15.920 --> 00:08:17.200
the problems with performance.

00:08:17.839 --> 00:08:22.399
Another kind of cool thing that can happen in here is that you don't only have to deal,

00:08:22.399 --> 00:08:26.239
you don't actually have to have the parquet file here on your laptop.

00:08:26.239 --> 00:08:28.880
The parquet file can be somewhere else.

00:08:28.880 --> 00:08:33.919
If you're writing code that looks like this, it again, you're not having to change the

00:08:33.919 --> 00:08:35.840
way you write code very much.

00:08:35.840 --> 00:08:43.520
We still have the, we still have very similar, like, read parquet DuckDB, group by, summarize,

00:08:43.520 --> 00:08:44.320
arrange.

00:08:44.320 --> 00:08:51.039
But now I'm going to a parquet, some enormous parquet files that are very far away.

00:08:51.039 --> 00:08:56.000
And when I am writing, when I'm writing and running this code, it is like, it is like

00:08:56.000 --> 00:09:00.159
running really fast, because it actually is not bringing everything into memory.

00:09:00.159 --> 00:09:01.520
It's like super speedy.

00:09:01.520 --> 00:09:03.679
I'm able to iterate really quickly.

00:09:03.679 --> 00:09:09.119
It's only when I do something that actually, that actually materializes it, that it starts

00:09:09.119 --> 00:09:14.559
to be like, okay, now it's actually doing the whole query and bringing it into memory.

00:09:15.119 --> 00:09:20.239
When you're working in this kind of mode, in an IDE, like I'm showing Positron here,

00:09:20.239 --> 00:09:23.919
there are some things that help you understand what it is that you are doing.

00:09:23.919 --> 00:09:28.640
I want to highlight just the, just the printing, like, as we can like look around, we're getting

00:09:28.640 --> 00:09:31.119
the cues that tell us what it is that we're doing.

00:09:31.119 --> 00:09:37.280
So I can notice that this, this df object here, it tells me it's a DuckPlier data frame.

00:09:37.280 --> 00:09:41.200
So I can think, oh, yep, I don't actually have that in memory in R.

00:09:41.200 --> 00:09:45.679
If I'm looking up in the variables pane, you actually notice it says question mark rows,

00:09:46.320 --> 00:09:49.280
question mark rows, because it has not been brought all the way over.

00:09:49.280 --> 00:09:52.960
So we don't actually know how many rows are in it at that point.

00:09:52.960 --> 00:09:57.200
This is a good, this is good, because that means we're able to write the code really

00:09:57.200 --> 00:09:59.679
quickly that we need to know to get forward.

00:09:59.679 --> 00:10:05.919
In this case, the only thing that has like actually come over into R is the data that

00:10:05.919 --> 00:10:07.440
we use to make this plot.

00:10:07.440 --> 00:10:11.520
So this plot was actually made by R with an R object.

00:10:11.520 --> 00:10:16.640
And so that, you know, which is only 24 numbers here, right, rather than maybe millions of

00:10:16.640 --> 00:10:21.679
rows, like that makes us have this good, healthy, quick workflow.

00:10:22.400 --> 00:10:27.520
So let's go over a couple of tips for what it's like when you work with a situation like

00:10:27.520 --> 00:10:33.440
this, when you use lazy evaluation, meaning we're not actually saying what are these numbers

00:10:33.440 --> 00:10:35.359
for real until we actually need it.

00:10:36.320 --> 00:10:42.080
The first is to get clear on what some of this, what some of this verbiage means.

00:10:42.080 --> 00:10:46.400
So DuckDB is an engine for executing queries.

00:10:46.400 --> 00:10:51.919
It can execute queries for a lot of different things, like a SQLite database, actually a

00:10:51.919 --> 00:10:52.719
CSV file.

00:10:53.039 --> 00:10:59.599
But one of the things that's especially powerful at working with is Parquet files.

00:10:59.599 --> 00:11:06.239
Parquet files, that's a file format, like a way to save something to some kind of a file

00:11:06.239 --> 00:11:09.919
on either your local computer or a faraway kind of computer.

00:11:09.919 --> 00:11:13.919
So it's good to get some understanding of what these different words mean so that we

00:11:13.919 --> 00:11:17.039
can have, you can have clarity and understand that it is not magic.

00:11:18.000 --> 00:11:23.039
Another tip I'll say is that working with lazy queries can get some, take some getting

00:11:23.039 --> 00:11:23.760
used to.

00:11:23.760 --> 00:11:29.359
And actually, the kind of the first stuff you do is feel so fast that you're like, yeah,

00:11:29.359 --> 00:11:30.159
yeah, yeah.

00:11:30.159 --> 00:11:33.840
And then you'll like accidentally do something that brings it into memory.

00:11:33.840 --> 00:11:38.000
And the whole, like the whole thing slows just like comes crashing to a stop.

00:11:38.000 --> 00:11:41.200
And you're like, oh, crap, I accidentally materialized it.

00:11:41.200 --> 00:11:45.119
Like this is a very common kind of thing to happen when you have this kind of workflow.

00:11:45.200 --> 00:11:49.440
And so it can take some getting used to of dealing with like what's it like to deal with

00:11:49.440 --> 00:11:54.479
something that is actually not in memory and feel super speedy until you maybe accidentally

00:11:54.479 --> 00:11:59.200
bring the whole thing into memory by materializing when you didn't need to.

00:12:00.479 --> 00:12:04.799
The translation between dplyr and DuckDB is pretty amazing.

00:12:04.799 --> 00:12:11.039
Like we can write a familiar domain-specific language.

00:12:11.039 --> 00:12:16.000
But it is true that there are not every single thing is supportive.

00:12:16.000 --> 00:12:18.880
You'll notice I didn't write group by summarize.

00:12:18.880 --> 00:12:20.880
I wrote summarize by.

00:12:20.880 --> 00:12:23.119
So there are some differences to be aware of.

00:12:24.000 --> 00:12:31.440
I also, if you yourself have to directly read and write parquet files, I would invite you

00:12:31.440 --> 00:12:33.280
to look at the nanoparquet package.

00:12:35.200 --> 00:12:38.880
That's a very useful package if all you need to do is read and write them.

00:12:38.880 --> 00:12:44.799
If you use something like read parquet with the nanoparquet package, it doesn't do lazy

00:12:44.799 --> 00:12:45.840
evaluation.

00:12:45.840 --> 00:12:47.119
It reads the whole thing.

00:12:47.119 --> 00:12:48.960
But sometimes that is what you need to do.

00:12:48.960 --> 00:12:53.440
You do need to like read and write them with like a lightweight fast package.

00:12:54.080 --> 00:13:02.000
And once you're dealing with files that are not on your laptop, often the most hard thing

00:13:02.000 --> 00:13:06.799
to do is not the R code you need to write or like keeping track of how these things

00:13:06.799 --> 00:13:10.559
work, but like dealing with some of the messiness around authentication.

00:13:10.559 --> 00:13:14.000
So that's just something to be aware of as like one of the pain points here.

