So the architecture, like when you think about where is stuff, is similar to what I just

00:13:34.000 --> 00:13:37.200
showed you, where it's on your laptop.

00:13:37.200 --> 00:13:40.640
You have your IDE, such as Positron, and your R session.

00:13:40.640 --> 00:13:45.520
And then R itself is connecting to something else on a remote server.

00:13:45.520 --> 00:13:50.239
A database is different from a parquet file in that it's not one single file.

00:13:50.239 --> 00:13:53.919
Databases are so interesting, so cool.

00:13:53.919 --> 00:13:57.599
There's like whole academic research around them.

00:13:57.599 --> 00:14:02.719
They have these, similar to DuckDB, like they have these query engines inside of them that

00:14:02.719 --> 00:14:08.719
are like finely honed to be super efficient.

00:14:08.719 --> 00:14:15.919
So they maybe solve these problems around memory and around performance in similar ways

00:14:15.919 --> 00:14:20.799
that maybe using DuckDB and parquet does, in that you don't have to bring everything

00:14:20.799 --> 00:14:21.440
into memory.

00:14:21.440 --> 00:14:26.320
You can have the database with millions and millions of rows, and you can use a query

00:14:26.320 --> 00:14:31.280
engine to get a smaller summarized result out that you can then do something with.

00:14:31.840 --> 00:14:37.280
So if you were going to write code in R to access a database and do something, you would

00:14:37.280 --> 00:14:38.159
do something like this.

00:14:38.159 --> 00:14:43.039
First, you would create a connection to your database, and then you would pull out a table

00:14:43.039 --> 00:14:47.359
from that database, and then do something like group by summarize again here.

00:14:47.359 --> 00:14:53.520
I'll notice that as this is printed out here, once again, it's giving me some cues by how

00:14:53.520 --> 00:14:56.640
it's printing that this is not an R object.

00:14:56.719 --> 00:15:04.559
So once again, we're executing a query, getting a preview back, but this is not yet an R.

00:15:04.559 --> 00:15:09.359
And once again, if you were to use an explicit gesture like collect, that would then bring

00:15:09.359 --> 00:15:10.080
it into memory.

00:15:10.080 --> 00:15:12.880
So now this thing is an R object here.

00:15:13.520 --> 00:15:22.080
So when you're working with a database in an IDE like Positron, again, you have some

00:15:22.080 --> 00:15:26.559
nice supports for how is it that you go about dealing with it.

00:15:26.559 --> 00:15:30.080
So I'm writing, again, really similar R code up here.

00:15:30.080 --> 00:15:36.479
I'm interacting with it in a way that it's giving me those cues about when I am and I'm

00:15:36.479 --> 00:15:42.559
not having this thing in memory versus one of the previews of what is going on with the

00:15:42.559 --> 00:15:44.000
database remotely.

