And your files, whether they're parquet files or some connection to a database on another

00:17:26.000 --> 00:17:31.599
server, like the separation between what's local and what's remote is actually now kind

00:17:31.599 --> 00:17:36.000
of between the front end and the back end of the IDE itself.

00:17:36.000 --> 00:17:39.359
This is something RStudio doesn't support and cannot support.

00:17:39.359 --> 00:17:43.199
And so it's kind of like a unique thing you might choose to use Positron for.

00:17:43.199 --> 00:17:46.079
This is what it looks like when you're working in remote SSH.

00:17:46.079 --> 00:17:49.359
So it looks very comfortable, very similar.

00:17:49.359 --> 00:17:55.199
But we get some sort of clues in the IDE about what is going on.

00:17:55.199 --> 00:17:59.199
Like here, you can click on the ports and see how all the ports are getting forwarded

00:17:59.199 --> 00:18:00.239
and whatnot.

00:18:00.239 --> 00:18:04.959
So my tips for dealing with remote SSH sessions, this one is a little different.

00:18:04.959 --> 00:18:06.160
This one is a little different.

00:18:06.160 --> 00:18:12.079
It's like the terminals that you have in the IDE, your files, your extensions, they're

00:18:12.079 --> 00:18:13.839
all on the remote server.

00:18:13.839 --> 00:18:18.319
They're not local at R. R itself is on the remote server.

00:18:19.280 --> 00:18:23.119
There's some kind of nice features we have around how you set this up.

00:18:23.119 --> 00:18:29.280
If you set this shutdown timeout quite long, you can actually close Positron locally.

00:18:29.280 --> 00:18:30.560
You can shut your computer.

00:18:30.560 --> 00:18:34.400
And your long-running R process will keep going, like it will just keep going on the

00:18:34.400 --> 00:18:35.199
remote server.

00:18:36.000 --> 00:18:41.599
You can, if you're interested, use all of that infrastructure entirely locally, actually,

00:18:42.239 --> 00:18:45.199
which you might do if you have high reproducibility needs.

00:18:45.199 --> 00:18:49.199
This does not solve problems around memory and performance.

00:18:49.199 --> 00:18:52.800
And actually, everything gets slightly worse because you're like running it inside a mini

00:18:52.800 --> 00:18:54.160
computer on your laptop.

00:18:55.199 --> 00:18:58.079
But you might choose to do that for other reasons.

00:18:58.079 --> 00:19:00.319
And I bet you know what I'm going to say next.

00:19:00.959 --> 00:19:04.719
Well, often when you're working with remote sessions, again, like the hardest thing is

00:19:04.719 --> 00:19:05.119
off.

00:19:05.119 --> 00:19:08.000
It's not that you have to deal with different code.

00:19:08.000 --> 00:19:10.000
It's some of the details of going with that.

00:19:10.800 --> 00:19:13.680
And I will drop up some links here.

00:19:13.680 --> 00:19:21.119
Another option in this list of ways to work things are to work in a truly server-type

00:19:21.119 --> 00:19:26.479
environment where you log into a browser, and then you connect to a server that's running

00:19:26.479 --> 00:19:27.119
Positron.

00:19:27.119 --> 00:19:29.599
And you can do that via Workbench.

00:19:29.599 --> 00:19:33.040
And with that, I will say thank you very much.

